          <link xlink:href="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P47712"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://refgene.com/gene/5321"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15041029"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>ERK phosphorylation activates cytosolic Phospholipase A2 ( PLA2 ), thereby contributing to the secretion of leukotrienes and prostaglandins, leading to inflammatory responses.
(Leslie 2004)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="620" y="818" style="Ouput Nodes"/>
    </node>
    <node id="PLCG1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(LAT | PIP3) &amp; Syk &amp; Btk"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="http://refgene.com/gene/5335"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P19174"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19909365"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17947660"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.genenames.org/cgi-bin/gene_symbol_report?hgnc_id=HGNC:9065"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>LAT associates with both isoforms PLC-gamma 
Phosphorylated PLC-gamma generates diacylglycerol ( DAG ) and Inositol-1,4,5-trisphosphate ( IP 3 ) from Phosphatidylinositol-4,5-bisphosphate ( PI(4,5)P 2 )
(Alvarez-Errico et al., 2009, Cao et al., 2007)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="729" y="387" style="Boolean internal node 1"/>
    </node>
    <node id="Raf" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="RAS"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/5894"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P04049"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19565474"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.genenames.org/cgi-bin/gene_symbol_report?hgnc_id=HGNC:9829"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Active KRas (on late endosomes) recruits Raf1 (C-Raf) to elicit MAPK signalling.
Raf1, MEK1/2 and ERK1/2 may act in the outer side of the Golgi apparatus and attenuate proliferation.
Raf1 phosphorylates MAP2K1, MAP2K2.
(Yao and Seger, 2009)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="550" y="571" style="Reduced nodes 2"/>
    </node>
    <node id="Rac1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="VAV &amp; SLP-76 &amp; Bcr"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="http://refgene.com/gene/5879"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P63000"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22714419"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9712046"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.genenames.org/cgi-bin/gene_symbol_report?hgnc_id=HGNC:9801"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Rac1 is present in inactive state in the cytosol until the reception of extracellular signals by the cell. 
Upon cell stimulation, Rac1 is rapidly targeted to the plasma membrane. 
The main factors involved in this mobilisation are the Rac GEFs like VAV and phospholipids (PtdIns(4,5)P2, PtdIns(3,4,5) P3) and lipid rafts at the plasma membrane. VAV catalyses the disassociation of GDP from Rac1 by modifying the nucleotide binding site such that GDP is released and subsequently replaced. 
The incoming GTP occupies the nucleotide binding site and finally displaces VAV from Rac1 
(Bustello et al., 2012; Kawakami et al., 1998)</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="267" y="422" style="Boolean internal node 1"/>
    </node>
    <node id="RAS" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="GRB2-SOS | PKC"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="http://refgene.com/gene/3265"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P01112"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12782630"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17496910"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19615955"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.genenames.org/cgi-bin/gene_symbol_report?hgnc_id=HGNC:5173"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16488589"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This component represent the three isoforms (H-, N-, K-) of RAS.
RasGDP binds to Sos, leading ot the formation of RasGTP  
RasGTP keeps Sos inactive enhancing duration and amplitude of the output.
(McKay and Morrison, 2007)

RasGRP1 activates Golgi-associated Ras on this compartment.
(Quatela and Phillips, 2006)

K-Ras is found exclusively at the plasma membrane. 
H- and N-Ras are also present in endomembrane compartments, such as the endoplasmic reticulum and the Golgi apparatus.
(Caloca et al., 2003)

Processed K-Ras is confined primarily to the PM.
However, when its polybasic region is phosphorylated or targeted by Ca2+/calmodulin, K-Ras relocalises to other endomembrane compartments, including Golgi, endoplasmic reticulum and mitochondria. 

In contrast, H-Ras and N-Ras constantly shuttle between the Golgi and PM as a result of a constitutive depalmitoylation/repalmitoylation cycle.
Ras phosphorylates Raf1.
(McKay and Morrison, 2007)

H-Ras but not K-Ras signalling is dependent on endocytosis.
(Frehenbacher et al., 2009)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="545" y="512" style="Boolean internal node 1"/>
    </node>
    <node id="RasGAP-Dok1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="SHIP-1"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P20936"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://refgene.com/gene/5921"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/Q99704"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://refgene.com/gene/1796"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15557172"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.genenames.org/cgi-bin/gene_symbol_report?hgnc_id=HGNC:9871"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.genenames.org/cgi-bin/gene_symbol_report?hgnc_id=HGNC:2990"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>The adapter protein Dok1 recruits the GTPase activating protein RasGAP, which in turns inhibits SOS.
(Zhang et al., 2004)

</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1114" y="421" style="Boolean internal nodes 2"/>
    </node>
    <node id="SHIP-1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="FcgRIIB-P"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/Q92835"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://refgene.com/gene/3635"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19290926"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.genenames.org/cgi-bin/gene_symbol_report?hgnc_id=HGNC:6079"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>SHIP family members seem to play a central role in regulating the FcɛRI-inducible levels of PIP3. 
SHIP1 hdrolyses PIP3 and inhibits it and recruits Dok1.
SHIP targets the 5′ position of PIP3 for dephosphorylation and thus opposes PIP5 kinase while creating PI-(3,4)P2, which can bind to the PH domain of a variety of signaling proteins.
SHIP-1–null BMMCs showed increased responsiveness to FcɛRI stimulation and increased degranulation and cytokine production, demonstrating the importance of SHIP-1 in maintaining control of mast cell responsiveness.
(Gilfillan and Rivera, 2009) </comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1233" y="258" style="Boolean internal node 1"/>
    </node>
    <node id="SLP-76" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="Syk"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="http://refgene.com/gene/2885"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P62993"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19909365"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20610546"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10811803"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.genenames.org/cgi-bin/gene_symbol_report?hgnc_id=HGNC:6529"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Cytosolic adapter SLP-76 recruits Vav1, Btk and adapter proteins Nck and SLP-130.
The LAT/Gads/SLP-76 complex creates a platform for the recruitment of multiple signaling molecules, including PLCgamma1, GRB2, NCK, Rho GEFs, VAV, and the Tec family kinases ITK and BTK.
(Alvarez-Errico et al., 2009; Balogopalan et al., 2010; Zhang et al., 2000)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="177" y="331" style="Boolean internal node 1"/>
    </node>
    <node id="Syk" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="((FceRI-IgE-P &amp; Lyn) | (Syk &amp; ERK)) &amp; !cCbl"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="http://refgene.com/gene/6850"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P43405"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19909365"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.genenames.org/cgi-bin/gene_symbol_report?hgnc_id=HGNC:11491"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Spleen Tyrosine Kinase is recruited by the ITAM region of FceRI.
Syk phosphorylates LAT1, LAT2,SLP-76,Btk,SHC,Clnk,3BP2 and possibly Gab2.
Tyrosine phosphorylated ITAM in FCERI gamma subunit serves as docking site for SYK (spleen tyrosine kinases), whereas the beta subunit ITAM has an extra tyrosine and is shorter than canonical ITAM which makes it unfit to bind SYK. 
Association of SYK to FCERI gamma subunit disrupts the COOH terminal SH2 interdomain interaction of SYK causing a conformational change opening the molecule leading to its activation 
(Alvarez-Errico et al., 2009)
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="298" y="233" style="Boolean internal node 1"/>
    </node>
    <node id="VAV" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="Syk"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/Q96D37"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://refgene.com/gene/7409"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1909365"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11340169"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20610546"/>
          <link xlink:href="http://www.genenames.org/cgi-bin/gene_symbol_report?hgnc_id=HGNC:12657"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>Guanin nucleotide exchange factor Vav1 catalyses GDP/GTP exchange on Rac1 and thereby activates it.
Activator of RAC GTPases, it is redistributed in the plasma membrane and is phosphorylated following engagement of FCERI. 
Phosphorylated SLP-76 tyrosines Y113 and Y128 (112Y and 128Y in mouse) provide binding sites for the SH2 domains of VAV. 
The binding of VAV to these phosphotyrosine residues may link SLP 76 to the Jun amino terminal kinase (JNK) pathway and the actin cytoskeleton. 
(Alvarez-Errico et al., 2007; Manetz et al., 2010,; Balagopalan et al., 2010)</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="267" y="360" style="Boolean internal node 1"/>
    </node>
